segments.text: I'll ask you that question one more time.

What do you feel, then, since you've been here, what, nine years, some of the highlights or some of the things that have happened, and I also, everybody's been reluctant to share their contributions because they feel like somebody else should talk about it, and I have heard some of the things that you've done.
Most of it has to do, a lot of it has to do with what you have brought into the university through all your grants, but
Even maybe some little personal insights or anecdotes that I would not find in the documents that are just from Linda Parrish.
Well, my greatest, if you ask anybody, people would say my greatest contribution has been bringing in several million dollars into Texas A&M.
To me, that's not my greatest contribution at all.
Okay.
I do that because it seems to me that the things I do need doing for the state of Texas, and that is helping disabled students access quality education.
And that's why I do that, not to bring big money into Texas A&M.
It happens that that supports graduate students, and those are good byproducts.
I do that because there are things that need to be done in Texas.
Say that, helping disabled students?
Access quality education in our schools.
I think that's the main thing, the reason I do that.
And it's just not to bring money.
Although, as you heard at the development committee, our provost was saying, you brought in this much money and we want you to bring in this much more money.
If it was just bringing in money, I'd say,
That's not the point.
The point is to do products.
Last year's grant are those two blue volumes there.
And as a result of writing those materials, we have about eight different universities now teaching a class similar to the one I teach here that we didn't have materials for.
So those things are really important.
But bringing in just the money is not important.
I would say that for the university, my greatest contribution and the greatest highlight for me
was being elected to the faculty senate the first year it was founded at A&M.
I was one of eight women in the entire university that got elected and one of two women that got elected to the executive committee.
And that

I guess will always be the most important thing to me is that I was trusted by my colleagues to be voted in from the college bed and then trusted by all the colleagues in the Senate, primarily men from other colleges, to run the Executive Committee.
And that, to me, is really important because what we've done in the Faculty Senate has
really changed Texas A&M.
Ask the students.
They'll tell you a lot of things.
You know, we're making senior state exams.
They hate that.
You know, and those aren't the important things.
Those are the things that get pressed.
But there are important things.
As of next year, we'll have a core curriculum where people could use to come to the university and get through an engineering degree and not know how to write a memo.
They'll never be able to do that again.
And it's only because of the fact they're safe.
And that, to me, that's made a contribution.
So in other words, the core curriculum came about as a result of something that the faculty said it saw a need?
The only reason.
The only reason.
The faculty said, this is ridiculous.
If we're calling ourself a world-class university and you can get out of here without taking an English class, without understanding anything about humanities, then this is not a university.
But you get a lot of resistance.
Oh, it's terrible.
My husband was the one who proposed the core curriculum for this university.
And he has really gone through quite a lot as a result.
But he's enjoyed the fruits of it because it's finally passed.
And everybody will see the value.
Or they already do, I'm sure.
Absolutely.
Well, so good and so dumb.
But the history of our university is so diverse.
It's not like a...
what you expect a major university to be.
Why do you think there's been so much resistance?
Because now every department or every college has to go and adjust their requirements so that it will fit into the core curriculum, or will they adjust it?
Oh, everyone has to.
Everyone that has an undergraduate program at Texas A&M has to include the requirements of the core curriculum to make sure that our graduates, when they leave here,
know a little bit about the broad basis of education.
But to do that, do they have to take away some of their courses?
That's what I mean by adjustment.
I know they'll all have to comply, but what is that going to do to them?
I imagine that's what some people have done.
Now, we didn't have to in education because we tend to be a broad-based liberal arts type-oriented discipline.
Those in engineering who have screamed, and agriculture who have screamed the loudest about it, were the ones who had such...
such straight-laced courses that they tended to promote themselves, and you can't live without 14 hours of this same thing, right?
And quite frankly, some of those may have to go to a fifth-year program as a professional school.
Or drop some of the things and maybe what not.
That's right.
I mean, we even had a college dean from the business say that, you know, it was not necessary to take 12 hours of banner.
You know, you can do with a lot, because there was not an opportunity then.
That's right.
We've just been feeding ourselves by saying, the more classes I make you take, the more classes I teach, and the more faculty we have, and then we're just like a dinosaur.

I think all of these things are just extremely important, and when I retire from Texas A&M, if I retire here before I leave or do something else, I think there will be nothing more important than the establishment of the Faculty Senate and the things that it's done.
And if you will share some of those things, because I don't have any documents on the Faculty Senate.
If you have anything that I could do, I would really appreciate that.
Are there any inside anecdotes, any kind of observation, something that stands out in your mind besides your contribution?
Is something that happened that was kind of neat, that was totally off the record, that is not documented anywhere, just your own?
About within just my personal relationships with people?
It could.
Yeah, that would be different.
Oh, gee, I'd really like to think so much about that.
I guess...
I think about just the way I was hired was incredible.
When you come to a school to get your doctorate, you never in the wildest estimation think you'll be hired there.
I never did.
I never thought, I never applied to be here, anything.
I was getting my degree, I was finishing up my dissertation, and sent out a letter and was...
flown up there for an interview, and when I came back, Dean Huber had heard I went, and called me up to his office and says, how did you like Minnesota?
And I said, well, it's terrific, it's cold, etc.
And he said, well, I tell you what, Linda, he says, if you'll call them right now and tell them to take you off their short list, we'll hire you here.
Well, it was just like, I could not believe it.
My husband was here, my children were here, it was just something we never considered, you know.
So when I look back at that, I think, man, was I lucky.
Now, on the other hand, I have to say that goes against everything I believe as a faculty governance person to say, who has the right to hire?
A dean shouldn't have done that.
The department should have decided, do we need somebody?
What kind of person do we need?
Do we search for someone?
But in my case, nine years ago, or ten years ago when I was hired,
on me that, you know, this was probably not appropriate, but it was something that he did, and I was grateful for it.
And that was typical of that administrative partnership.
That never happened.
It would not.
I just don't believe it would ever happen again.
There's things to change.
That's right.
Is there anything else that you'd like to share and...
In conclusion, anything that you want to include?
And it can be negative because I didn't put any negative questions in.
I don't know whether maybe I should.
Maybe this is too Pollyanna.
Maybe not.
It's not realistic.
I'm finding that there's a reluctance.
I don't know if it's the tapes or what, but there's a reluctance to get into things, and it doesn't have to be on tape.
I'm being quite candid with you.
I appreciate that very much.
I don't really care because people do either know how I feel about things.

The only way to be a great university, which I think we are, is to be a, and I'll use this again, lovingly critical one, to care enough about the place where you work to be able to see if there's something that can be done.
And I think we are now at that point where we can do that.
In the past, we have been, yeah, we're great, we're great.
We can float on Texas A&M's reputation.
and say, of course we're great.
We're at Texas A&M.
I've done that a lot in my life.
But now we are so good in the College of Education that we can say, we need to change this.
We need to do this, and we can even become happy.
That's something that we constantly need to do, and then that will signify how good we are.
Do you think that the majority of the faculty is...
adaptable enough to go along with drastic changes like that?
It's getting that way with more retirements.
And I hate to say that right after you've talked to Jim Boone, because Jim Boone is the most open-minded, forward-looking person we have, and he's retiring.
So it's not all... You can't really classify older with that, because he's wonderful.
But...
I think that some of the new young excellent and given the opportunities they'll be able to get.
I think sometimes we don't think we're good enough ourselves and occasionally when I visit other good places I just think, my goodness, I work with some of the best people in the world.
And I love to come back and let them know that.
The other day at the Development Council, I told Brian Copco, I said, you know, this is my favorite part.
Because to hear a little sketch on my floor is, for example, or Stan Carpenter or, you know, whoever, David David, we ought to do that more often.
The recognition of teachers, we could never do enough.
I know, because they're wonderful.
And I work two doors down from Vi, and we just take each other for granted.
And I just love hearing that about the people who wear those awards.
Well, I'm sure we all heard the same things about you when you got it.
Well, it makes you feel good.
It really does.
But it also reminds us, and we too often forget,
of what tremendous talent that we have just around the corner.
And you know what?
My husband, well, let me conclude by telling you that I really appreciate you giving me all this time, and I hope that I can come back and pick your brain a little bit more.
If things come up where I can call you to ask you a question, and that we'll tie all this together when I get everybody's interviews and then start putting the pieces together.
That'd be good.
And I'm going to get you a transcript.
I hope so.
